        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Typical sizes of CTTS disks are a few hundred AU (e.g. Andrews et al. 2009, 2011), with inner holes &lt; 100 AU. Thus, a spatial resolution around 0.4 arcsec is appropriate to resolve the inner hole at a distance of 150 pc and at the same time ensures that the beam is large enough to encompass the entire signal, so that the size of the inner hole and the total size of the disk can be measured in the reconstructed image. We confirmed this with simulations in the ALMA Observation Support Tool. 
This proposal aims to image the disk in the dust continuum, so we propose to use the widest bandwidth available to improve the signal-to-noise ratio. If the disk remains undetected, this observations will set a strict upper limit. Figure 3 shows the spectral energy distribution of MN Lup. Clearly the bands known so far do not require any IR excess and thus do not indicate any circumstellar  material. The ?-symbol shows the sensitivity limit of 0.04 mJy that will be reached in the proposed observation. This is 2.5 orders of magnitude below the typical 1.3 mm flux for an accreting CTTS, using a stellar mass of 0.7 M_sun
(Strassmeier et al. 2005) and the relation between spectral types and 1.3 mm flux from Andrews et al. (2013). If no signal is detected, the dust mass in the disk must be below 0.1 Earth masses (total disk mass 10 Earth masses).
Since the SED of the proposed disk is not known before the observations, there is some uncertainty to what the best band is, but if the accretion is fueled by the disk, the signal will be strong enough to be detected in any ALMA band. We propose observations in band 6 to facilitate a comparison with the large sample of CTTS disks already observed with the SMA.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
