    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>MN Lup is a pre-main sequence star in the Lupus star forming region. Its young age is evidenced
from the equivalent width of the Li line in the optical spectrum. Accretion onto the star, although
at a very low accretion rate, is indicated by three diﬀerent lines of evidence: (i) MN Lup has a
broad Ha line; (ii) Doppler imaging shows a ring of hot accretion spots and (iii) it has a X-ray soft excess and high-densities in the X-ray spectrum that are otherwise only seen on accreting stars. Still, no IR excess is found in Spitzer out to 24 micron. An accretion rate of about 2e−11 M_sun /yr is required to explain the Ha emission lines and the X-ray spectrum. The most promising explanation is that MN Lup is accreting from a proto-planetary disk with an inner hole much bigger than seen in any other T Tauri star so far. Thus, we propose to search for this as yet undetected disk of cool dust with 1.3 mm observations. A non-detection would be even more interesting: In this case the accreted matter must be supplied by a compact object in a smaller orbit; in other words, a non-detection of a dust disk implies that MN Lup could be eating up a hot Jupiter right now.
</prp:abstract>
